hands_on_practices.problem:
Let the underlying semantics be that of classical two-valued propositional logic, where truth values are $0$ (false) and $1$ (true). A set of Boolean connectives is called functionally complete if every Boolean function on finitely many inputs can be expressed by a formula built from those connectives. You are to decide the functional completeness of the set $\{\to,\leftrightarrow\}$ using Post’s functional completeness criteria, which characterize functional completeness in terms of exclusion from certain closed classes of Boolean functions.

Define the indicator value $I$ by
$$
I \;=\; \begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } \{\to,\leftrightarrow\} \text{ is functionally complete},\\
0 & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$

Determine $I$ and justify your determination by explicitly identifying which of Post’s closed classes (if any) contains all formulas built from $\{\to,\leftrightarrow\}$, and by arguing why this containment follows from the semantics of the connectives and closure under composition. Your final reported value must be the single number $I$. No rounding is required.
